    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1889-03-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1889-03-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="226" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d226">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Hubbard</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1889-03-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">March</hi> 15,
                            1889</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 291.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your interesting dispatch No. 547 of the 14th
                        ultimo, in relation to the promulgation of the new Japanese constitution on
                        the 11th of February last, has been received and the accompanying papers
                        have been filed as part of the history of this memorable event.</p>
                <p>The people of the New World, who have ever testified a lively interest in the
                        welfare and progress of Japan, can not but view in this formal adoption of a
                        scheme of constitutional government a bright augury for the future of a
                        country and a people bound to them by so many ties of continued friendship
                        and intimate intercourse. That this measure will secure the liberties and
                        promote the happiness of the Japanese people and tend to secure for their
                        empire the autonomous position which rightfully belongs to it in the
                        concourse of nations can not be doubted.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">James G. Blaine.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
